# CLAUDE RULES - Vibe Coding Guide Documentation Project

These rules guide AI development of the Vibe Coding Guide documentation.

---

## Project Context

**What:** Comprehensive guide to AI-assisted full-stack development
**Goal:** Document proven methodology for building production-ready apps with AI
**Audience:** Developers, founders, CTOs, technical leaders
**Style:** Professional but accessible, practical not theoretical
**Example:** RISE project (github.com/The-Low-Code-Foundation/rise)

---

## Documentation Standards

### 1. Chapter Structure (REQUIRED)

Every chapter MUST have:

```markdown
---
title: Chapter Title
description: One-sentence chapter description
---

# Chapter Title

## TLDR

[2-3 paragraphs max covering:
- What this chapter covers
- Why it matters
- Key takeaways
- Estimated time/effort if applicable]

---

## [Main Section 1]

[Content...]

## [Main Section 2]

[Content...]

---

::: tip [Optional Callout]
[Practical tip or key insight]
:::
```

### 2. TLDR Requirements

Every TLDR must be:
- **Scannable:** Bullet points or short paragraphs
- **Complete:** Someone reading only TLDRs understands methodology
- **Actionable:** Clear what reader should do
- **Concise:** 200 words maximum

### 3. Writing Style

**DO:**
- ✅ Use "you" and "we" (conversational)
- ✅ Include real examples from RISE or other projects
- ✅ Provide copy-paste templates
- ✅ Explain WHY not just HOW
- ✅ Use code blocks for prompts, configs, examples
- ✅ Cross-reference other chapters
- ✅ Include cost/time estimates where relevant

**DON'T:**
- ❌ Use passive voice excessively
- ❌ Write academic/theoretical content without examples
- ❌ Create examples that don't work
- ❌ Assume reader knows context
- ❌ Skip the "why this matters" explanation
- ❌ Make claims without evidence

### 4. Examples Requirements

Every example must:
- Be **real** (from RISE or actual projects) OR clearly labeled as hypothetical
- Be **complete** (enough context to understand)
- Be **testable** (prompts actually work, code actually runs)
- Include **commentary** (explain what's happening)

**Format for conversation examples:**
```markdown
**You say:**
```
[Your prompt]
```

**AI responds:**
```
[AI response with thinking shown if relevant]
```

**Why this works:**
[Explanation of the pattern]
```

### 5. Template Requirements

Every template must:
- Have `[PLACEHOLDERS]` for customization
- Include comments explaining each section
- Actually work when filled in
- Include example of filled-in version

**Format:**
```markdown
### Template: [Name]

**Purpose:** [What this is for]

**Template:**
``` ```markdown
# [PROJECT_NAME]

## Overview
[Description of what this project does]

## [More sections with placeholders]
``` ```

**Example (filled in):**
``` ```markdown
# RISE

## Overview
Desktop application for low-code AI-assisted development...
``` ```
```

### 6. Cross-References

When referencing other chapters:
```markdown
See [Chapter Name](/path/to/chapter) for details on...

As discussed in [Philosophy & Approach](/part-1/philosophy)...

We'll cover this more in [The Cline Workflow](/part-3/cline-workflow).
```

Always use relative paths, always link first mention of related topic.

---

## Content Verification Checklist

Before marking task complete, verify:

### For Each Chapter:
- [ ] TLDR present and complete
- [ ] All sections from outline covered
- [ ] 2+ real examples included
- [ ] Templates provided (if applicable)
- [ ] Cross-references valid
- [ ] Code blocks formatted correctly
- [ ] Markdown linting passes
- [ ] Frontmatter present and correct

### For Examples:
- [ ] Prompts actually work (test them)
- [ ] Code examples run without errors
- [ ] Real project examples accurate
- [ ] Commentary explains the pattern

### For Templates:
- [ ] Placeholders clearly marked
- [ ] Comments explain each section
- [ ] Example provided
- [ ] Template is complete (not missing critical sections)

